Feedback:
For Alchemist Feedback Summit:

REALLY need more breaks in between sessions.  Way too tiring for an all day event.

Re: Tyche
Good pitch.  Uniqueness of the technology not evident.  Approach to the insurance industry seems like a logical start.  Need to tie in pricing with potential cost savings to the insurers.  Not clear exactly how the service is tied into external database search; how well the company does this will be key to success.

Xendo
Very interesting. Well presented and good potential. 
- I Liked the approach and the notion of search across devices and data sources
- The expert network search is a 2nd product. Probably tell a different story.

Excellent business plan and team.  They have a very good understanding of the customer problem, how they will validate, and how they will do customer development. .  No additional suggestions.  We will follow up with them

Great meeting you. Interesting business. Big market if you can capture it. Mission critical for insurance companies for a time. Competition will drive margins down over time, so make sure you have a plan for holding on to customers once you have them and charging more to them for more services over time.  Going after big companies can kill your business. I wonder if you can hook a smaller insurance company to use as a test and reference account first. I would move you from a 4 to a 6 after you get a reference customer on the hook

Carrum Health
Very thorough written deck analyzing the market potential.  Great backgrounds of the team on the business side.  Given the size of the customers here early traction will matter a lot.  I have questions around how much value can truly be captured by an intermediary player here so any validation of pricing discussions would also be good before a large round can be raised.  Definitely worth pursuing more, I look forward to continuing the discussion.
Very strong founder and business model.  Strong business model.  Need to hit whatever milestones required to raise Series A, hire great team and accelerate.  Will introduce to Dave Schwab.

Very timely business plan in the area of expertise analytics in enterprise.  The team has a very good understanding of the problem and how to gain market traction.  Presentation was very good.  Overall no additional suggestions for improvement.  Critical success factor will be for them to establishe a beachhead with SMB.  Several large companies in enterprise analytics already have their in house solutions in this area.

Work on how the business will work down the road. Will people write databases to your API? If you are not the standard with network effects, your business will commoditize and lose its value. Very cool that you are moving the ball forward on big data speed.You are a 4 for now, but would move to a 6 or 7 if you figure out a good business model.

Tyche
- Good idea. Obviously very early in the process, so it is clear that a lot of work is needed ahead.
- Adam is a high-energy guy but came across as if he was a bit tired, so some of the comments during the pitch seemed slightly dismissive ("I won't bore you with the details"). 
- Don't assume that the audience knows the insurance industry: Yes, it is big, but don't skip on mentioning how many $B are in play within the specific vertical and products you are targeting
- Careful with the lingo. Most people won't know what a Loss Ratio is, and why .9 is better than 1.1 in that case. Most people not familiar with the industry are prepped to think that bigger is better. 
- Insurance is in great need to be disrupted. Keep working on it!

Very cool company!  I like the moon shot aspect of it.  Smart, professional, passionate founder.  I would refine the video to a more polished version that would tell a complete story.  I'm going to ask In-Q-Tel if they're interested in talking to them at lunch tomorrow.

Secured3D
I like the demo of the cloud-connected dashboard, down to the webcam connection, well done!  As you are finding out through your partnership discussions, this will be a complicated ecosystem for a while longer  I suggest you simplify your first go-to-market to just the cloud orchestration/management piece and reserve the high-end security pitch and market-making design stuff for down the line--otherwise you run the risk of appearing too unfocused for a young company.  Real customer use cases will be key here for a larger funding round.

Re: Xendo
Pain point is a real one, probably more acute at the SMB level than large enterprises.  Cross-cloud search has been around for some time, but if this solution can address key shortcomings of earlier solutions it may succeed.  Key value is to extract new learning and knowledge from the enterprise, as business adopt cloud solutions at a faster pace.

Recommendation is to continue to deploy the priced model and gauge how the business scales.  SMB approach for first pass seems right the right approach.
sorry. forgot to answer the scale.

Good pitch.

Recommend focusing on the "unfair" advantage that you have vs others.  Eventually, the incumbants will over a mobile GUI, so need to show that have something even better

waygum.

interesting play. technically sophisticated and pilots are going to show a lot about how long/challenging it will be to roll out...and what the sales cycle will be. might be tricky raising capital w/o more pilot user data

Great chutzpah. Big vision. I am concerned about too much not invented here. I think there may be better technologies that come along that you may miss if you keep thinking you can do it all. Also, the business model requires a lot more thought. Sometimes people come out of Singularity with great ideas, but miss the practical side of making a business work. You might just have what it takes, I believe good people will work hard for you. $15 million is hard to raise. You might want to try a plan B, where you can make it fly with less money. Go get em.

The team and the pitch were good.  Domain expertise of the founder in particular, in the telecom/carrier space is critical.  The pain point seems strong, but the value proposition of the solution will improve significantly once it incorporates recommendations/proposes next steps in addition to simple monitoring.  

The go to market strategy is commendable, I like the idea of approaching smaller players and also branch offices before addressing large carrier headquarters.  Good that 3Ten8 has already demonstrated traction.  I have no doubt that this will be a solid single digit $M company.  Key challenge will be to grow the business beyond that.

To prepare for further investment, spend more time demonstrating the unique technical merits rather than pitching this as an already established technology that is just being applied to a new market segment.

Analytics to address carrier churn has been tried by several startups.  A few have already been successful.  Key challenges for this startup are:
1) Establishing a specific niche around carrier churn analytics
2) Getting quick adoption by smaller regional carriers to achieve critical mass
3) Selecting the few VCs who are still willing to fund startups aimed at carriers.

The positives are:
1) Team understands and has a good history with carriers
2) Already have revenue customers
3) Good advisory team

Very big idea, possibly the biggest that i have seen this year.Chad is driven, passionate and compelling. Presentation needs work to make it more consumable - did a good job of making the case for the market opportunity (which could actually be shorter) but then struggled to articulate why his approach to building a QC is unique and differentiated. Also, can do a better job of simplifying what they are doing. Also, need to lay out some interim milestones between now and the 4 years mark. for example, what will it take to deliver a proof of concept ?
Good founder/CEO.  Clear problem statement and solution.  Looks like a very big market.  Tough to gauge technology without technical founder.
Strong interest in follow up.  I'm the one that gave you my card.  Please contact me.

• Insertion strategy is key what markets will you go after first and how (what is the low hanging fruit, where can you get the most reference customers etc)
• How are you going to maintain pricing variability factors for the different markets that you service (if it's event / holiday for hotels,  seasonality for some widgets and so on)?  Doesn't this just shift the knowledge gathering to you?  What do your margins look like given this upkeep needed?
• What will you do about liability if your algorithms happen to be wrong (down side protection when you're messing with pricing is a necessity) 
• What is your ideal exit?

Again I think all these questions are easily answered, it's just a matter of how you organize them into your pitch.    Well done and a great story.

A pleasure speaking.

I'd focus on 2 areas:
(1) differentiating your sell through SP vs sell to consumer directly.  Each will require different products and go-to-market
(2) validating that routing companies will support your agent

I really like the open cloud architecture.  The biggest challenge that you'll need to overcome is how to get your agent installed.  In cases where SPs sell the rouer (ie 2Wire) it will be easier.  Though really hard for the direct to consumer

Price optimization and analytics is a very current and timely problem .  So market timing and what the startup is offering is attractive.  Need to work on a formal presentation so that the story is easier to follow.

Great opportunity. Focus on market size. I am not sure how big this gets. I do think it is interesting that you can charge every time someone prints a unit. Good energetic team $5 million is too much to ask for now, and I don't think you need that much right away.

Ladera Labs
Great progress with getting to working prototypes and field customer deployments with very little funding!  The BOM needs to come way down from where you are to be able to afford retail channel distribution and a price point in the $200s without killing your margins.  The value proposition and setup out of the box is not as easy to explain as an in-house thermostat would be, so I suggest you narrow down the focus to 1-2 key features only for your first product--could be just better UI coupled with instant information and control from a mobile device.  Sensors/smart adaptability etc can follow later.  Know that many VCs will not touch this because of the hardware component.  Good job getting going with real customers!

I like the business model and the founder.  I hate project management software and see a need in the market for exactly what they do.  One of the key challenges is how to show that it really is easy to use and intuitive.  Recommend that he use a short, 10 second video of a reference customer to make the point that it's different.  Great passion and commitment.

Good overall business concept.  Lack of pitch slides made following the story very difficult.  The team seems to have experience in the pricing space which will help with execution.  Initial customers are good (AirBnB, EventBrite, etc) but the roster will need to grow substantially.  Potentially much broader applicability to healthcare, energy, and other verticals where real time pricing might be important.  It is also possible to pivot this business into other forms of optimization rather than only pricing.

Recommend slides for any future pitch.

Cool name.
- Would be great if you add why companies are ditching / changing their performance reviews
- Provide statistics & proof on why next-gen performance reviews can actually improve performance / culture / company morale, etc
- The consumerization of everything + incumbents being slow story can be powerful. 
- Right now it is unclear who are the incumbents (aside from successfactors, which seems very sales oriented). 
- Are there specific verticals that are better suited? You mentioned company size, which was good. Is this a better system for software companies, manufacturing companies, etc?
- Distribution is not the same as data sources. You can use the same platforms for different things in the process - Use diagrams to communicate clearly where each part connects.
- A demo would be great to have. Showiing a 1-minute video of the product in action would be amazing.
- You have a great vision, don't be afraid to say so explicitly.

Very smart technologists, made a ton of progress early in the incubation phase. During the incubation phase, focus on:
1. Finishing the product and getting 2-3 beta users who have the product in deployment, even if its in a limited use case
2. Building deep relationships (ideally go to market partnerships) with DataBricks and Nvidia
3. Add 1-2 advisors who have S&M experience within the enterprise

Great presentation!    Nailed the presentation.

Need to figure out a way to not be positioned as an asset management company.  Check out Cisco's pitch on Internet of Everything

As you scale outside of  IT, think about how do find the right buying center.  In operational environment, it won't be IT that cares.  It also wont' be facilities, so need to find the right sales model to make this work.

Let's talk soon

Badger Maps
Great product/market fit, simple product, UI looks cool and useful, love the early traction with individual users across multiple companies.  The big question is around the size of the opportunity: can the product scale beyond an add-on for CRM+geo to a location-aware mobile orchestration platform for all relevant functions of the outside sales rep?  Need to talk more about that but I think there is great potential here, would love to follow up.  Great job!

Re: Righetti Quantum Computing
Very strong technical team.  Great idea, but very high risk and potential for being highly capital intensive.  Amount of funding requirement probably vastly underestimated.  The commercial opportunity - and technical leap relative to "business as usual" transistor based technologies should be better discussed.  This is a high risk investment but with potentially high upside potential.  That upside needs to be better quantified. May be difficult to secure the talent required to get the company off the ground.

Overall, a good pitch that evidences strong technical capability.  More emphasis on the business opportunity encouraged.

Good start. Very entrepreneurial. Able to get 300k sign ons in a short time without much money. The market is crowded, but if it truly is as easy to get on as you imply, people will try it and you can keep adding features, paid and free. I Like that you might be able to make it on so little money, I am concerned about the people being so spread out around the globe making this happen.

Great presentation, one of the best of the day.

Clarify that you are selling to the LOB, not HR.  And talk about how valuable that is, vs HR directly.

For the LOB, i'm guessing improving results are the most important thing.  So, how do you create a company to solve that pain point, and then differentiate from all the other companies that will follow you.   

Think more about your sales and marketing model when you really need to scale the model - it must extend beyond just word of mouth

Re: Rigetti
This is a very technology intensive startup.  Challenges are:
1) Very few VCs  are funding chip / systems companies
2) $20M funding that the startup is citing is probably underestimating what it will take to get to a viable company
3) Presentation needs to address customers and how it will get traction
4) More business expertise required on the team

Very good team.  I like the business model a lot.  Good pitch.  The company appears to be at a point where it makes sense to raise money and accelerate.  Founders are reluctant to leave bootstrap mode.  Would recommend that they tap into the Alchemist network to get guidance on how to identify the right investors, both in terms of character and value added potential.
price optimization as a service is an interesting idea. continuing to understand/refine target market and what that means for product/easy of use/ultimate 'best' price obvious next steps for them

Like the idea/product. Value proposition is very clear and there is a market need. Team has accomplished a lot with no external capital. Having working product in market (20 beta users) was very impressive. Areas of improvement:
1. Flesh out the go-to-market (its OK to have 2 options - B2B, B2C at this stage)
2. Lay out what you will do with the $ 1 M seed round and what are the key milestones at which point you will be ready to raise a Series A
3. Team needs more marketing dna, especially to explore the B2C GTM. A potential channel is the Apple stores. Check out Automatic as another case study
4. Focus on getting 1000 systems installed and getting customer feedback to definitively answer the question, "does the product work?" by th etim eyou raise a Seris A

ParallelX
Strong technical backgrounds of the founding team.  Impressive technical achievement for the company!  However, for most investors the techno-speak is going to go right over their head.  Need customer testimonials or at least pilot benchmarks/tests to show applicability of approach in real-world situations.  The R/T applications (ad RTB, etc) are good potential targets for pilot deployments.  I also like the GPU vendor partnership angle, to the extent you can get pulled into customers by much larger vendors.  I foresee a challenge in staying independent to build a big company, the upstream and downstream vendors are going to want this functionality integrated more tightly with their offerings and an integrated sales approach makes too much sense here.  Great job cracking a tough technical problem and good luck with the first pilot deployments!

Secured3D

Interesting approach and certainly a problem that needs to be addressed. Love to learn more about how you think about next steps and what 3D printer companies do themselves.

Analytics and natural language processing for insurance / risk analytics is a promising market but covered by both large players (IBM Watson) and other startups.  Natural Language processing has been worked on for over a decade. Hence, here are the key recommendations:
1) Technology and business model differentiation needs to come out much more strongly.  
2) Company becomes much more fundable if its articulated as a core natural language platform and insurance and risk analytics is the first segment being executed
3) Presentation needs to address why this is a big company, not just what it will do for insurance / risk

The storyline needs work. 
- Seems like the go-to market strategy is not clear
- Working on a platform within a vertical is a risky proposition unless the market is huge, there is an ecosystem to be supported, and there is enough fragmentation yet a common set of problems that would justify the existence of the platform. The deck did not have a market size element of TAM, showed 2 examples of verticals but no pain point was clear, and it was unclear to me that there is an ecosystem to be created (btw I believe there should be, but it didn't come across)
- Delivery was rushed and it was hard to understand the different sections of the deck. Make sure to practice pitching your story with different time limits so you can make your point get across each time.

Good team and demo pitch.  Clear story.  Great idea.  Unclear if/how it scales.  It could be huge or it could go nowhere.  I'm wondering if there's a service, recurring revenue business model that you could set up that could be preloaded with challenges that would issue weekly or monthly and continually test a company' sites for a fixed or success based fee.

scrappy, driven entrepreneur who has accomplished a lot with very little money/resources. Acquiring 300,000 users is very impressive. Areas of improvement:
1. provide more data around what users do with the product, and how sticky it is
2. the business model needs to be fleshed out, ad supported software requires consumer scale (10s of millions of daily users). More likely, this will be a free-mium model 
3. Need founders to be based in one location

SupplyBetter
Very good presentation pace, good structure, key points covered.  Need more specific funding ask against the proposed milestones.  I still have questions around the addressable market size for a marketplace maker in this space, given the nascent stage of 3D capabilities for part manufacturing around the world.  Good job getting early transaction proof points and documenting client feedback.
Great business model and team.  Huge market.  Professional polished pitch.  I am introducing to Tyco SVP HR if he's willing to do call.

Great credibility of the team being PayPal alums. That's one of the key differentiators.  Use that to your advantage.
It's a crowded space you're competing in, with lots of competition at every side of the value chain, with different business models, technologies, etc, and overall lots of money being poured in. You need to cut through all that noise with a clear message that distills your strategy.
Get ready to address competition. We all know it's crowded, so make it clear you are aware of all these companies.
- This sector has low barriers to entry, but high barriers to scale. Your partnership with PayPal gives you a unique distribution channel to be exploited.

• Margin model and burn rate descriptions are key
• how you are going to monetize the modules and the priority / markets you're going to target are a critical part of your story 
• adding partnerships to get the connected services selling you is also a key (I should be able to find you on ever notes market place for example) 
• getting people on full time and quickly 
• shaping the pitch and defining differentiation, sustainability and defensibility are critical. 

Great stuff...  I'll definitely try it out

Great idea, focused on a hard problem/market, with a disruptive solution. Team has made strong progress, both on the supply (companies) and the demand side (testers). 
Focus for the next 3 months should be to define a go-to-market approach and validate the unit economics (LTV vs. cost of customer acquisition).  Ideally do so for 1-3 mainstream verticals where you can demonstrate a substantial TAM.

What are the features of Nest and Fitbit that you combine?

Buzzline - an IOT company is too broad and non-descriptive. 

What parts of system are going to extend to other verticals over time?  Have you architected the system to be module so you can extend quickly.

Play up analytic angle.  This seems to be big.  

I didn't like the 2x2 that compares price to ease of use.  Seems like you'd make it more focused for commercial focus.

I'd suggest focusing on one segment, then showing your plan to win there.  Ie pick consumer or commercial

Rigetti Quantum Computing
Love the confidence and the technical backgrounds of the founding team.  Taking on a huge technical challenge, will be a science project for a few years.  Definitely worth a meeting with VCs that know something about this space (like Steve Jurvetson at DFJ).  My feedback is to try to articulate a funding program that can bring in grant and other $ to complement equity capital raised from investors--the track record of pure "science project" investments is not good--government or research grants can help mitigate the need at least for the first couple of years.

• small commercial / real estate are your best early customers 
• building partnerships with utilities, municipalities is a critical component of your GTM.   
• I really think that certification via LEED an perhaps other "green" certifications will help your marketing substantially.  It's the icing on the money saving, labor saving, hassle saving layer cake. 
• you have to figure out what your desired exit is going to be.  Is it selling to somebody like RainBird or some other sensor/timer company? Is it IPO? 
• need a phased insertion strategy i.e.. small commercial, large commercial, developing world ag, US consumer etc etc...
• I'd be careful of IoT messaging.   May not be as effective as you think

the presentation needs the following info to make it more complete:
- go to market, user acquisition
-market size info, competition info
- business milestones, projectons slide. projections can be customer numbers, and or, product developments, $$, etc.

The design of the deck is great. Clear and simple. Good job on that front.
Consider highlighting what the specific problem you are solving for is. Deck currently does not clearly explain the problem. Good platform pitches often show a few use cases that they solve (in your case, a google cal, FB event, Eventbrite, etc). Currently hard to connect pitch with what the problem is.
Don't get lost in the sea of a massive market. Demonstrating that you have clear use cases will help you demonstrate you have a clear idea on how to attack the market.
Metrics to keep an eye for (potential comps)
- Tracking pixels that companies like AdRoll / Kayak install on websites
- Other 'buttons' installed (pay with paypal, bill me later, buymenow, etc)
- Think of what categories of websites will yield more 'event visibility' in the short / medium / long term. What are a few 'whales' that if you knock down will make your button ubiquitous.

Interesting solution and product
I like the team
I did not get the use case right away and I have spent a good bit of time int his space
Explain the product and relationship between the expertise and search better
I think there are more compelling use cases for this technology in teh enterprise
Mention how many customers are paying

Not sure if my earlier comments were lost  so I'll redo quickly 

- Partnerships and route to market are key 
- Building credibility beyond bit coin is critical 
- being able to show the effect of your service in a white paper, testimonial, etc is a key piece of marketing 
- need to flesh out the incentive alignment story more effectively.  Very good way to introduce the service. 

I'd love to talk more.

1) Extremely crowded market in collaboration and project managementsoftware --  differentiation for Freed camp is not yet compelling enough
2) Revenue model is extermely challenging.  How will they get users to pay and get recurring revenue.  Different from Linked In and Facebook in that these applications were first or a kind and extremely viral.
3) Not enterprise focused
4) Demo was not compelling enough.

I would advise the team to really focus on differentiation and business model so they stand out in a crowded space.  Also are they ultimately targeting the enterprise.  Most top VCs will see this as a "me too"

I like the focus in the underserved SMB retail market.  Good fit with the disconnect between the huge move towards mobile by consumers and the lack of sophistication and solutions in this area in the retail SMB market.  Strong founder.  I'd like to see more detail on the mechanics behind the system... things like how the small retailer maintains the system, adds pictures, sets minimum inventory, etc. but I understand it's only six minutes!

Pitch needs to be better structured so that they can cover the presentation within the allotted 6 mins. 
Strong technical team, was very impressed by the fact they have launched a beta product directly to consumers in India. Key thing that the team needs to do is to demonstrate product-market fit, i.e. is there a significant base of consumers that will give up control of their phone experience in return for free data ? and is this segment of consumers valuable to advertisers ? Also, while going to market through telcos makes sense, it is also a challenging way to build a business.

Re: Freedcamp
Angel is a passionate entrepreneur.  The rest of the team was not covered in the pitch.  This market is highly competitive and there is still not sufficient market evidence that customers will be willing to pay for Freedcamp's premium products.  This does not appear to be an enterprise-focused startup.  Competitive space, and the product demo was not too impressive - felt fairly standard without a knockout factor.  Revenue traction, given that company has been around for 4 years, is very low and this is probably an indication of similar hurdles to be expected in the future.

Overall, good energy from Angel but I see difficulties for the business over the longer term - will be hard to scale.  Does not in its current manifestation appear to be a differentiated solution addressing a critical market pain point.  Will be a tough sell to investors.

PerfectPrice
Great relevant backgrounds of founding team.  The value proposition makes sense at a high level but, given the history of prior attempts in this space, the proof will be in the pudding.  Need early customer traction either in e-commerce or another vertical to get VCs seriously interested, a description of the technical capabilities alone won't cut it.  So I suggest that you focus all your efforts in the short term to completing pilots with alpha customers and getting references or quantitative proofpoints of the value of you technology.  Also suggest exploring partnerships with personalization vendors to come into pre-qualified customers that have the capabilities to leverage your product.  I would not recommend meeting with VCs until you have more customer engagement proof points, suggest you look at a seed round first to hire the 2-3 engineers you need and get the first pilots done.

Re: Oomnitza.
Delivery was fast.  Slower pace recommended.  Stage of the business according to Arthur beyond most of the other startups.  Company has started with IT assets and appears to have been successful; now moving to other verticals.  I'd recommend more details on the technology; differentiation was stated but would be good to have more evidence of competitive advantage.  Tesla is a great first win in the manufacturing space, but TBD whether others are forthcoming.  Good overall.

Re: Oomnitza
1) Hits an important aspect of IOT segment with asset management.  Timing and market are good.
2) IT asset management is an easier first market but real value will be  getting an early foothold in enterprise asset management of machines and other equipment before others enter the space.
3) Challenge is how they compete vs. big players like Tivoli, Maximo, etc.  They need to think about how they execute a disruptive business model vs. incumbents.
4) Initial marquis customers/ partners like Tesla are very impressive.
5) Presentation needs to be delivered more slowly and methodically.  Top VCs will be interested in the substance and quality of the content.

compelling team and good market traction to date. explained the value proposition and overall market very well. 
financial, product and sales milestones needed to answer "what's next for the business" question. add info on go to market, customer acquisition topics as well.

Novel idea, targeting a real pain point. Strong customer traction (100 customers, 1 customer paying 100K/yr). Steve has a strong S&M background: Team needs to:
1. Articulate the size of the opportunity, is this a $ 1 B revenue market or a $ 100 M revenue market ?
2. Better explain what the product does and why it is defensible ? felt like a feature vs. a product based on the presentation
3. Lay out the go-to-market model and explain the unit economics (for customer acquisition)

The idea of the platform to connect the devices in the connected home is good. That part is clear, but should be communicated more concisely. 

The part that was not clear to me is that the company has a clear understanding on the market segments and what the drivers for adoption will be. Going with a niche modem provider doesn't seem like the channel that would provide mass market adoption. I would argue that the install base of modems will not renew very often (no figures were provided to prove me wrong), and that the OEM market is much larger (i.e. the average user won't go and buy a custom modem, they will use whatever Comcast provides). Thus, developing and communicating a clear strategy to get the product into the installed modem base would be necessary for me to buy into the idea.

Compelling  product
Crowded space
Need to highlight difference right away
Compare yourself to others; what's different
Freemium is not a sustainable difference
explain revenue model more clearly - you started with freemium and later circled back to pricing
change the name - don't want to continue to ride on top of base camp

Very interesting, unique business model.  I like the founders.  Strong advisor group.  I like the event layer for the web.  It looks like a huge market.  I'd like to get more clarity on exactly what the target customer looks like, wall the laments of the solution today and in the future for that customer and how the revenue grows as more elements of the solution are deployed.

OpenNode
I'm not an expert on network infrastructure management software so take all this with a huge grain of salt.  I liked the customer traction and team technical expertise in the area.  I'm skeptical of the ability of a small company to build a big independent SaaS sales force around infrastructure management for large customers--I suggest you pursue either closer OEM-like partnerships with the cloud vendors or tighter top-down referrals with the provisioning/application management guys.  I'm also concerned that early customer traction with government-type customers could keep you in the professional services/consultative solution space (and therefore distracted from a pure product focus) for a long time.  From a presentation perspective, I needed more details on why the product is truly differentiated from others in the space.
OpenNode:  Skype call slowed down my understanding a bit..but faster up front clarity of what the technology/offering would have been helpful.   Crowded market -- more on this offline

Strong presentation, compelling need identification and professional look and feel
- Create a TAM and revenue forecast or SAM that is specific to the Xendo product
- Need to address security up front - it will be a big issue for customers and investors, don't let the listener ask the question first
- Explain why SaaS products are especially positioned to create a better enterprise search solution b/c their data is organized in a uniform fashion

1) Team and market need are great
2) Concern is number of competitors going after the same space...not doing something brand new.
3) Key thing for the team to focus on over the next months is acquiring customers;  doing something clever in the business model or customer segmentation (perhaps vertical niche) that will give investors confidence that they can scale much better the their competitors.
4) Should maximize partnership with Salesforce and Google
5) Should explore  if Microsoft is excited about working with them.

Re: Groove
Very good pitch.  Team seemed strong, but may need deeper technical expertise.  Recommend defining the unique selling point of the business more clearly (probably a combination of security, customizability and performance).  Currently the addressed market is small and specialized (Salesforce/Google apps).  Good to have early focus, but longer term there should be a plan to grab larger market.  Competition seems to be a concern.  Need to shorten and simplify sales cycle if possible. Google background of the founders is a strong point.

very interesting and fundable idea. really liked the presentation. was a little high level - recommend making it more specific to the solution they have built. also, including milestones, traction, learnings, etc. anything that demonstrates current business status would be helpful. also, information on high level financial model will help. go to market strategy was missing too.

Interesting idea in an emerging market, but not clear that they have an understanding of what is required to get product-market fit. Team did not talk about their go-to-market,  or what their business goals/key milestones are. CEO is very passionate, has done a really good job of getting the company off the ground. Not sure that he is the right CEO to build the business.
